rrsa: PKCS#1 v1.5 decrypt error paths are a Bleichenbacher oracle
\`r_rsa_pkcs1v1_5_decrypt\` (rlib/crypto/rrsa.c:805) decrypts the input via the constant-shape \`r_rsa_raw_decrypt_internal\` and then walks the recovered plaintext looking for the PKCS#1 v1.5 EME-PKCS1 padding structure:

\`\`\`
if (size < 11 || buffer[0] != 0x00 || buffer[1] != R_RSA_EME_PKCS1)
  return R_CRYPTO_INVALID_PADDING;

ptr = buffer + 2;
while (ptr < buffer + size && *ptr != 0) ptr++;

if (ptr - buffer < 10 || ptr >= buffer + size)
  return R_CRYPTO_INVALID_PADDING;
ptr++;

if (*outsize < size - (ptr - buffer))
  return R_CRYPTO_BUFFER_TOO_SMALL;
\`\`\`

Two distinct attacker-observable signals are emitted from this block:

1. **Error-code divergence.** \`R_CRYPTO_INVALID_PADDING\` (no 0x00 0x02 prefix, or PS shorter than 8 bytes, or no terminating 0x00) vs \`R_CRYPTO_BUFFER_TOO_SMALL\` (padding looks valid but the decrypted message is longer than the caller's output buffer) vs \`R_CRYPTO_OK\`. This is the textbook Bleichenbacher 1998 oracle: an adaptive attacker submitting crafted ciphertexts \`c · s^e mod n\` for many \`s\` values learns which fall in the \"PKCS-conformant\" range, and binary-searches the original \`m\` in ~2^20 oracle queries for a 2048-bit modulus.

2. **Timing divergence.** The \`while (ptr < buffer + size && *ptr != 0) ptr++;\` walk terminates at the first 0x00 byte in the random-looking PS field. The execution time correlates with the position of that byte, which is determined by the decrypted plaintext, which is determined by the ciphertext + key. Even if the error codes were unified, the time-to-return would still partition ciphertexts.

This is the same class of attack as ROBOT (Böck, Somorovsky, Young, 2017) which broke ~7 vendor TLS stacks and is still cited as the canonical \"don't roll your own PKCS#1 v1.5 decrypt\".

## Threat model

Any caller that exposes \`r_rsa_pkcs1v1_5_decrypt\` to an attacker who can submit ciphertexts and observe one of: the return code, the latency, or whether the caller proceeds with the decrypte

